4... exd4 5. Nxd4 Bb4
{ The established main line for the last 500 years... Well, maybe not that long ago, but the oldest game I have with this position is from 1873. }
6. Nxc6
{ The only move. There is no other move available to make Bd3 possible, which is desirable because Bd3 will comfortably cover the threatened e4-pawn. }
6... bxc6 7. Bd3
{ We develop the Bishop and cover e4. Now Black most of the time will go for d7-d5, either immediately or after castling first. This is the most respectable way for Black to play, playing according to the motto that Black is OK in the open games if he gets in d7-d5 unpunished.The absolute main line of the Scotch Four Knights features this approach, but Black has two main ideas to avoid the main line.   1. not playing d7-d5 quickly, but rather delaying it or going for a d7-d6 setup.  2. playing d7-d5, but trying to use move order tricks or concrete tactics. }
