{ We are using the same setup as against the Pirc. Quite often, a quick ...Nf6 by Black will indeed transpose to the Pirc. In general, the whole complex with d6/g6 is full of transpositions. Don't be too intimidated by this fact - White has a strong centre and will have at least a decent position with common sense moves. }
4... Nd7 5. f4
{ And we will transpose after Black goes ...a6 or ...c6. Nd7 has little independent value. One setup, that may occur via various move orders, is the Hippopotamus  (or just Hippo)  , which involves e6/d6, Knights to d7 and e7 and a Queens Bishop Fianchetto. Let's have a look at this via the 4... Nd7 move order, though Black might also start with ...e6, a6, b6 etc. - it is more of a setup than a concrete line. }
5... e6 6. Nf3 Ne7 7. Bd3
{ This is the setup that White should go for against the Hippo. We build a strong centre and support it with the Bishops. }
7... b6 8. O-O Bb7 9. f5
{ In this concrete position f4-f5 is already quite strong. Note that Black may go for different move orders, so you are not guaranteed to get precisely this on the board. But against the Hippo this is a standard idea. Another plan might be Qe1-h4, especially if Black has started with an earlier Kingside build-up and castled already. }
9... exf5 10. exf5 O-O 11. Qd2
{ And White has good attacking chances on the Kingside. } *

