1. e4
{ Hello and Welcome to the Quickstarter Guide for Keep it Simple: 1. e4 ! The Quickstarter Guide provides an overview of the most important lines and ideas of the suggested full repertoire. It features the most commonly played lines and therefore studying this guide gives you the opportunity to be ready to employ this repertoire before studying all the dedicated chapters move-by-move. It is the ideal way to start your journey into the world of 1. e4, but it will also be useful at a later stage to give you a condensed overview of the material. Let's get started with some chess moves ! }
1... Nf6 { My choice against the Alekhine is to play } 2. e5
{ This must be best, but I need to mention that I checked  2.Nc3  as well. The main reason to consider this alternative is that we play the position after 2... e5 3. Nf3 anyway, arising from the Petroff/Russian Defence move order. However, the issue is  2...d5  , after which I don't see anything too promising. You can investigate  3.e5  , but after  3...Nfd7  I didn't see anything better than to allow a transposition into the French Defence - and this is a line we don't have in our repertoire. Long story short - just push the e-pawn ! }
2... Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4
{ Theoreticians usually view  4.Nf3  as the critical move, and I agree. The practical problem behind 4. Nf3 is that Black chooses the defensive setup, so you need to be prepared for a wide range of lines. In the 'Playing 1. e4' book by John Shaw the author devotes a huge chunk of the book to fighting the Alekhine's with this line, but I don't think it is very practical to learn all the details when you will get the Alekhine's once in a blue moon. Our choice still carries some punch while being easier to learn. }
4... Nb6 5. exd6
{ White has good chances for an edge with this line while being reasonable in terms of study time. It still puts some considerable pressure on Black without being overly theoretical. Now Black has a very fundamental choice between recapturing with either c-pawn or e-pawn. There is a general consensus that taking with the e-pawn is solid for Black, but White usually should have a slight pull. On the other hand, taking with the c-pawn is sharper, but has been under a cloud for quite a while due to a certain setup that we will investigate soon. I think this is actually quite playable for Black, but White can still pose some serious problems, of course. Let's have a look. }
5... exd6
{ The solid, conservative move. The symmetrical structure should be a little bit better for White, as we have more space and the more active pieces. A way to view this position type is to call it a Petroff/Russian Defence structure with Black's Knight being slightly offside on b6. }
6. Nc3
{ Our setup includes Nc3/ Bd3/Nge2. The main point of this setup is to make Black's c8-Bishop look a bit silly. Black usually tries to pin the f3-Knight with Bg4, so we avoid Nf3 completely. The Nge2-based setup has some more concrete ideas that we will investigate now. }
6... Be7
{ The most popular move, preparing to castle. Instead  6...Nc6  will often just transpose to the same positions. }
7. Bd3 Nc6 8. Nge2
{ Instead,  8.Be3  would transpose to the lines we looked at via 6... Nc6 7. Be3. Keeping the Bishop flexible is even more promising for White here. }
8... Bg4
{ A key idea is to realize is that  8...Nb4  is met by  9.Bb1 !  , keeping the Bishop. Black can't take with  9...Nxc4 ??  due to  10.Qa4+. }
9. Be3
{ Protecting the d4-pawn, which was just attacked, due to the pin on the e2-Knight. }
9... O-O { Again  9...Nb4 ?  10.Bb1  is strong for White. } 10. b3
{ This is an important finesse. Alternatives don't convince as much:  10.f3  is not so great because of  10...Bh4+  , disrupting White's setup.   Instead,  10.O-O  allows  10...Nb4  , as  11.Bb1  is not working now - Black just takes on c4. }
10... Bf6 11. O-O Re8 12. h3 Bh5 13. Qd2
{ Unpinning the Knight and threatening to go Ne2-f4, netting the Bishop pair. }
13... Bg6 14. d5 Ne5 15. Bxg6 Nxg6 16. Ng3
{ White enjoys a very easy game. We have more space and ideas to push the f-pawn. This whole line with exd6 promises White a small, but very comfortable edge. The game Gelashvili-Berkes, Minsk 2017 is our sample game for this line and well worth studying to better understand how this variation is played properly. }
