{ This is my suggestion, at this point, but White has some interesting alternatives.   The most principled move is  4.d4  , but this was too close to an open Sicilian for this repertoire. There is absolutely nothing wrong with it, it just does not fit well with our purposes.   Also, there is  4.O-O  , going for  4...a6  5.Bd3  !?. This is quite interesting as well but a tad too artificial for a 'keep it simple' repertoire. Again, nothing wrong with it, but it didn't work out for me in this context.  My chosen move opens up the c2-square for the Bishop and leads to position types that are more typical of the Ruy Lopez than anything else. One important point to remember is that Black intended to play a Dragon or Najdorf, most likely, and might not be well versed in defending a Ruy Lopez structure. }
4... a6
{ This has little independent value compared to Nf6 unless White tries to omit Qe2, which makes little sense. }
5. Ba4 b5 6. Bc2 Bb7 7. O-O Ngf6 8. Qe2
{ And we will transpose to the main line.   Instead  8.Re1  is possible, but not particularly better than the Queen move. }
