1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 g6
{ The Hyper-accelerated Dragon with 2...g6 is mostly played in order to reach a Dragon setup while avoiding the Rossolimo after   2...Nc6  3.Bb5   Or the Moscow after  2...d6  3.Bb5+. }
3. c3
{ White now has two main tries for an advantage:   The first is going for a Maroczy Bind with  3.c4  , followed by 4  d4.  This is probably most critical for Black, but White needs to study quite a body of theory, as Black chooses the setup. This means that you need to be ready for a range of lines. I decided against covering this complex option here as  g6  is a line you won't face very frequently.  Fortunately, there is a second option in 3 c3, which fits nicely with our repertoire choices against ...e6 and ...a6. After 3 c3 we again get a c3-Sicilian while avoiding the most respectable setups available to Black. In this version of the Alapin, Black is committed to ...g6 and has trouble equalising completely. Black now needs to choose when to play ...d5: right away, in order to recapture with the Queen, or wait until White has played d4. }
3... Bg7
{ This natural move is by far the most popular, but White has good chances for an edge against it. }
4. d4 cxd4 5. cxd4 d6
{ This move is too passive. Black does not attack White's centre at all and will suffer in a cramped position. }
6. h3
{ I like this prophylactic move best. White prevents Bg4, and Black struggles to find a good square for this piece now. }
6... Nf6 7. Nc3 O-O 8. Be3
{ White is better with natural moves, supporting the centre. } *

