1. e4 d5
{ The Scandinavian Defence. Black immediately defines the central pawn structure by forcing the trade of d-pawn against White's e-pawn. The coming pawn structure is quite typical for other openings as well, in particular there are similarities with the Caro-Kann. The Scandinavian is quite popular at club level, but not seen frequently in top events. What is the reason ? Well, the top players usually just want to force a draw with Black or, in some concrete cases, play for a win if the tournament situation demands it. The Scandinavian is unsuitable for either scenario: Black will often simply get a position that is just very slightly worse and that cannot be immediately drawn by some forced line. -On the other hand it is not particularly suited for drumming up some crazy complications, either. An additional issue is that Black will give up the Bishop pair, frequently, which is an important factor for strong players. These considerations are not as relevant at club level where Black will usually get a playable, if slightly worse position, without much learning effort. This is also the reason why Chessable Co-Founder IM John Bartholomew recommends the Scandinavian and has released a popular repertoire about it. With White we will get a comfortable position against the Scandinavian most of the time, but don't expect too large of an advantage - Black's structure is quite solid. }
2. exd5 Qxd5
{ I think this is probably better than Nf6. Against the Knight move White gets a slightly better position without any effort at all. }
3. Nc3
{ The most natural and probably best move. It has one drawback: White places the Knight in front of the c-pawn, so White does not manage to get the d4/c4 pawn duo early on  (compare with Nf6)  .   I always had some interest in  3.Nf3  ,  trying to delay Nb1-c3 until White has played c2-c4 first. However, nowadays this approach seems to be defanged by  3...Bg4  4.Be2  Nc6  etc. as also demonstrated in John Bartholomew's Scandinavian Repertoire on Chessable.  After 3 Nc3 Black has a choice of Queen moves. We will play with d2-d4 and Nf3 against all of them, in most cases followed by Bc4. A common theme is that Black develops with Bg4 or Bf5, against which we will often try to play with Kingside expansion. Let's check all the Queen moves, one by one. }
3... Qa5
{ This is the traditional main line, but it is not as popular anymore, as Black players began to appreciate that the Queen is a bit safer on d8 and that there is little concrete advantage in being on a5. }
4. d4
{ There are some interesting ideas here in delaying or omitting this move altogether, but I like to recommend something more classical for our repertoire. Going d2-d4, and Nf3 later, certainly makes a lot of sense. }
4... Nf6 5. Nf3 c6
{ This is the most common move, giving the Queen retreat squares.   @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/ppp1pppp/8/q7/3P4/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq  d3  1 4@@EndFEN@@ Often, this position is reached via the  4...c6  5.Nf3  Nf6  move order as well. By playing ...c7-c6 Black is not yet committing where the c8 Bishop will be developed. }
6. Bc4
{ The most active square for the Bishop. Note that against early Bf5 moves we go Ne5, intending Bc4 and g4. If Black delays the Bishop move to f5 we should start with Bc4, as the immediate 6 Ne5 may be answered with ...Be6, as played by Anand vs Kasparov in the only ever World Championship game that started with the Scandinavian. This line seems to be less challenging for Black, in my opinion. }
6... Bf5 7. Ne5 e6 8. g4
{ And we have reached the main line of our repertoire that is examined via the 4...Nf6 move order. As usual we need to play forcefully to put pressure on Black. }
8... Be4
{ This is no solution for Black's problems but needs to be answered precisely. }
9. O-O { Threatening g4-g5 to win a piece. } 9... Bd5
{ The only move to avoid an immediate loss. } 10. Bd3
{ The direct  10.f4  is also fine.  But 10 Bd3 avoids trading the somewhat unstable piece on d5 and is more logical, in my opinion. }
10... Nbd7 11. f4 { With an excellent position for White. } *

