{ @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/p4ppp/2p2n2/3p4/1b6/2NB1Q1P/PPP2PP1/R1B2RK1 b - - 2 11@@EndFEN@@  This position is part of our repertoire via   11...h6  12.Bf4  Bd6  13.Re1.  White is happy to trade the Bishops in these structures.  There are multiple reasons for that. On a very general note White's pawn structure is favorable and trading minor pieces should emphasize that  (similar to traiding in IQP and hanging pawns scenarios)  . More concretely, White may be able to fix the pawns on light squares and use the c5 square for a Knight - this is only imaginable without the Bishop on d6. Another common scenario is White pushing c2-c4 and taking on d5 later to give Black the IQP. Again this is more favorable without the Bishops, with better control over the key squares d4, c5 and e5. }
13... Bxf4
{ The main continuation is   13...Rb8  , as examined in the theoretical section. I think this is more precise than Anand's move which gives White more control over the dark squares. It is not a serious mistake of course, but little things tend to add up to real problems for Black in the main line Scotch Four Knights. }
14. Qxf4 Be6 15. Ne2
