{ A surprising decision, at least in my eyes. There are positions where the Black formation with a,c and e-pawn are fine, because the open files provide counterplay. Here however White will have an excellent Knight on c4 that covers b2 and Black's inferior structure is not easily repaired.  I would have expected   11...Bxc5  12.Rd1  Nbd7  13.O-O  and I'd slighty prefer White but Black is solid. }
12. Rd1 Qa5
{ The Black Queen will be offside in some moves, but this still looks like the most natural move.  Instead   12...Nbd7  13.O-O  Qc8  Looks quite passive and White has the simple plan to shift pieces to the Kingside, for example starting with  14.Ne3 }
13. Na3 Nbd7 14. O-O
{ Black now has to worry about Nc4, but at the same time he does not want to move the d7 Knight as it guards the e5 square as well. }
14... Nb6
{ Black decides to concede the e5 square.  Against   14...Bd5  the engine points out the excellent resource  15.Nd2 !  Now grabbing on a2 leads to serious problems.  Bxa2  16.Nac4  Bxc4  17.Nxc4  Qd8  18.Ne5  and White is much better. The threat is to win material on the d-file. In fact Black only has one way to avoid an immediate loss.  Nd5  19.Nxd7  Qxd7  20.Bg3  Qa4  21.Be4  and Black suffers. }
15. Ne5 Nbd5 16. Bg3 Rac8 17. Nac4
{ White's opening concept was successful. He's got very active pieces and the excellent posts on c4 and e5 for his Knights. }
17... Qa4
{ 17...Qd8  is not a happy move to play, but Black needs defenders near the King. }
18. Rfe1
{ Getting the rook centralized is very natural, but there was an even better alternative.   18.f4 !  White's play in this opening is mostly based on piece play, so pawn pushes like that are not very common. Here f4 is very strong, as f4-f5 would open up the kingside for the attack while the Black Queen is not well placed at all.  g6  stops f4-f5, but  19.Bh4  allows g2-g4 next for a strong attack. }
18... Ba8
{ This has a tactical problem.  After a move like   18...Rcd8  White is better, but it is nothing decisive.  One risk-free option  (probably not the best one though)  is to play  19.Qc2  when Black can't avoid the trade.  Qxc2  20.Bxc2  Now plans with Ba4 and Na5 are very annoying for Black to meet. }
19. Bc2
{ White certainly calculated   19.Nxf7 !  , but must have missed something. In fact this Knight sacrifice is close to winning for White.  Rxf7  20.Qxe6  One key point is the unprotected Rook on c8. Black's last move was Ba8, undefending this piece.  Rcf8   20...Qd7  21.Bf5 !  is a complete disaster.  21.Ne5  White will get more than enough material just by taking on f7, but the main problem is Black's uncoordinated piece placement.  Nb6  22.b3  Qe8  23.Nxf7  Rxf7  24.Qh3  Black is helpless against Bd6 and Bf5 ideas. }
19... Qa6 20. Bd3 Qb7
{ It looks like Black has spotted the Nxf7 idea. He prevents it and even threatens himself now. ...Nxc3 is on. }
21. Qf3 Qa6 22. Qe2 Qa4 { Black allows the strike again. } 23. Bc2
{ No, thank you. } 23... Qe8
{ Maybe Black needed a win in this game ? He avoids a repitition but misplaces the Queen in the process. }
24. Bd3
{ So White allows black to repeat again. Maybe he was thinking that Black will avoid it anyway, given how he played the last moves ? In any case, White could have avoided this possibility with many possible moves, he is still comfortably better.  For example   24.Bb3  was a way to continue.  Rd8  25.Na5  , intending Qa6. This is tough to stop, as  Rd6  26.Nxf7  Qxf7  27.Bxd6  Bxd6  28.Qxe6  Is better for White as well. }
24... g6
{ Black wants/needs to win it seems.  He could have claimed a draw with   24...Qa4  , allowing Nxf7 again - but White wouldn't get the chance to play it after the claim. Objectively speaking he should be happy with the draw. }
25. Ne3 Nc7
{ 25...Nxe3  was neccessary, but no fun either.  26.Bb5  Bc6  27.Bxc6  Rxc6  28.fxe3  Rc8  29.e4  and the pressure is mounting. }
26. h3
{ This is very strong, thinking about prophylaxis in the middle of a brewing attack. }
26... Nh5 27. Bh2 { White now threatens Nd7 ! } 27... f6
{ 27...Nf6  28.Bf4  and Bh6 is the next threat. Black is on the ropes. } 28.
N5c4 e5 29. Ng4 Qc6 30. f3 Rfd8 31. Ncxe5 { and the floodgates open finally. }
31... fxe5 32. Bc4+ Nd5 33. Nxe5 Qe6 34. Nxg6 Qxe2
{ 34...Qxg6  35.Qxe7  Nhf6  36.Qxa7  also falls apart. } 35. Nxe7+ Qxe7 36.
Rxe7 Nf6 37. Rxa7 Kf8 38. Be5 { The Bishops are completely dominating. } 38...
Rd7 39. Rxd7 Nxd7 40. Bd6+ Ne7 41. Re1 Re8 42. Bb5
{ In the ...e6 Alapin White has a simple, yet effective setup as demonstated in this game. All pieces are well placed and the superior activity might become the starting point of an attack on the Black King. }
