1. e4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. Nc3 Bg4
{ This is the traditional main line, but it has lost some ground in recent years.  The more fashionable lines are   3...dxe4  4.Nxe4  Nf6  and in particular   3...Nf6  One of the reasons for this shift is the frequently seen position type that we will examine in this game. It is very solid for Black, obviously, but also somewhat passive as we will see. }
4. h3 Bxf3 5. Qxf3 Nf6 6. Be2 e6 7. O-O Nbd7
{ As discussed in the theoretical section I think that this move is more interesting for Black. White does not get in d2-d4 so easily now.   7...Be7 }
8. d4 dxe4 9. Nxe4 Nxe4 10. Qxe4
{ This is the type of position you'll get quite often in the Two Knights Caro. White has the pair of Bishops and more space, but Black has no pawn weakness and with two minor pieces already traded his position is not all that cramped. The white strategy is to slowly expand and while doing so keeping and eye on Black's pawn breaks with the c- or e-pawn. Those pawn breaks are the only real plan that Black has in terms of changing the pawn structure. If we make sure they are not possible at all or at least unattractive our play will be much easier. Maxime Vachier-Lagrave does an excellent job in this game to demonstrate White's possibilities. }
10... Nf6 11. Qd3 Bd6
{ A natural development move, but there is more to it. Black would love to trade this bishop, getting rid of the long term concern of facing the Bishop pair. One way to trade is via f4, so Black intends to go Qc7 and Bf4. }
12. Rd1
{ I like MVL's concept of dealing with the Bc7-f4 idea.  A different approach is   12.g3  O-O  13.Bf3  , but I prefer to have the Bishop on c4 later, as we will see in the game. }
12... Qc7 13. Bd2
{ Of course   13.Qf3  was fine as well, preventing the trade on f4 differently. This is a bit more natural than the game continuation and probably more precise. }
13... Bh2+ 14. Kh1 Bf4 15. Be1
{ I know it might look odd, but placing Bishops on the back rank for later use is not rare at all. This is mostly applied in closed positions that are later opened up. }
15... O-O 16. a4
{ This is often useful to gain some space and possibly provoke a concession on the queenside. I am doubtful of the timing though.  I probably would have gone for   16.g3  first, clarifying the situation with the Bishop on f4.  Bd6  17.Kg2  Rfe8  18.Qf3  This is very similar to the game, just without a4 for the moment. This is important in some lines.  c5  The position type after the superior   18...e5  is examined in the note to move 16.  19.dxc5  Bxc5  20.b4  Bd6  21.c4  and White manages to get his pawn majority rolling. A moving majority combined with the Bishop pair can be a very powerful asset. }
16... Rad8
{ We need to check the very principled   16...e5  transforming the pawn structure to complete symmetry. One important aspect of this move: Black opens up the diagonal towards f7, which is an argument of keeping the white kings's bishop flexible  (see the note to move 12)  .  17.dxe5  Bxe5  18.c3  Rfe8  19.Qf3  I think it is equal here. White has lost a bit of time in the last moves and it is not clear that having played a4 actually helps. The bishop on f1 likes to be on the a2-g8 diagonal and often has a good, protected spot on b3, now this is not a stable square anymore. Still the game is not a draw of course, as White may still push his queenside pawns later. }
17. Qf3 Rfe8
{ Black has centralized and all pieces are dveloped, but what is the plan to make any progress ? Pushing e6-e5 was better timed the move before. }
18. a5 a6
{ That's the almost automatic response.  If Black allows the a-pawn further with a move like   18...Bd6  , we happily oblige.  19.a6  b6  20.g3  a6 will be an asset in any endgame and c6 looks like a weakness Black should rather avoid. It is nothing terribly bad for Black, but the game move is natural and better. }
19. Bc4 Nd5
{ Black from now on adopts a sit-and-wait strategy. I am very sceptical that this is a good solution, but maybe he evaluated ...e6-e5 as just too unattractive ? As Black you'll absolutely never win after the e-pawn push, while the game is worse for Black but it remains more complicated.   19...Bd6  20.g3  e5  was the way to go for the 'central clearance'. }
20. Bb3 Bg5 21. c4
{ Forward ! Still pushing c2-c4 is a choice that needs to be very carefully considered. There is one drawback: White weakens the d4-pawn quite seriously and we need to check that we have enough support for it or may advance it further. Note that once c2-c4 is played any Black pawn push c6-c5 or e6-e5 might be answered with d4-d5. }
21... Ne7 22. Bc2 Bf6 23. Bc3 Nc8 24. Rd2 Nd6 25. b3 Rd7 26. Rad1
{ By now the pawn pushes will never happen as White has too much control. Black is in full waiting mode now. }
26... Qd8 27. Bb4 g6 28. g3 Bg7 29. Kg2 Qc7 30. h4
{ Bent Larsen once said something to the effect that you should push the rook pawns if you don't know what else to do. In fact here it is very sound strategy as Black either has to allow the potential opening of the h-file or weaken himself. }
30... Red8
{ I think he should have played   30...h5  making it more difficult for White to find a straightforward plan. It's not easy to play the g-pawn and open up the kingside. White should manouvre slowly and probably try to get a later d4-d5 push going. While Black is passive his position is still a tough nut to crack. }
31. h5 Ne8 32. Bc3 Nd6 33. g4 Ne8 34. Qe3 Qd6 35. hxg6 hxg6
{ The first open file on move 36. } 36. Rh1 Qe7 37. Rdd1
{ White needs both rooks on the h-file. We need to keep in mind that this is a rapid game and now some inaccurate moves creep in. }
37... Qf6
{ This allows a strong continuation for White. Black had to wait with a different move. His situation is not very enviable, but there is no clear win for White in sight yet. }
38. Rh3
{ Here   38.Bb4 !  was strong, controlling the f8 square ! Now Black does not have anything better than  Rxd4  39.Qh3  R4d6  giving up the exchange with a large, probably winning advantage for White.  If Black tries to avoid this and goes   39...Nd6  he runs into problems on the d-file.  40.Rxd4  Qxd4  41.Rd1  Qe5  42.Qg3 !  This is very strong.  Qxg3+  43.fxg3  c5  44.Bxc5  Bf8  45.Bb6  Ra8  46.Bc7  Ne8  47.Bf4  And White is winning. }
38... Qe7 39. Rhh1
{ Being able to correct your mistaken decisions is very important. Black threatened to play e6-e5, so d1 needed cover.  Of course MVL checked the natural   39.Rdh1  , but Black has one defence. Only ONE, but it is enough !  Rxd4 !  40.Bxd4  Rxd4  And here I start to like Black's chances. He is not going to get mated anymore and e6-e5 and a Knight tour to e6 looks scary. White can prevent that but the game has turned around. }
39... Qf6 { Trying to repeat, which is very understandable. } 40. g5
{ We checked   40.Bb4 !  already on move 38. } 40... Qe7 41. f4
{ That's the point of MVL's play. He tries to establish a full pawn bind, preventing all breaks. }
41... Nd6
{ Here Black absolutely needed to play   41...c5 !  , all other moves lose ! It is not a trivial calculation at all though - in a rapid game this is very hard to do when you are low on time.  42.dxc5  Rxd1  43.Bxd1  Bxc3  44.Qxc3  and this is moment where you probably stop in your calculation. White threatens mate and after  Ng7  45.b4  keeps the pawn. However...  e5 !  saves the day for Black !  46.Qxe5  Rd2+  47.Kf3  Qd7  will end in a perpetual ! Easy for engines, but close to impossible to find and evaluate correctly with short time available. }
42. Qh3
{ Now there is no rescue anymore. The threat is d4-d5, looking all the way to the h8 mating square. }
42... Nf5 { 42...f5  43.Qh7+  Kf7  44.Rh6  doesn't help either. } 43. Bxf5 exf5
44. Rde1 Qa3 45. d5 { Finally this Bishop has its say ! } 45... Qa2+ 46. Kf1
{ And Black resigned, being unable to prevent the mate. This position type is a frequent guest in this line of the Caro-Kann. White always has a slight pull and needs to patiently improve his position. It seems that Black at best manages to simplify to a symmetrical position where he is claiming that the Bishop pair is not enough to win. It's all rather comfortable for White, being in no risk at all. }
