1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qd6 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3
{ One main task for White against 3... Qd6 is this position where Black has a choice of lines. They are all quite comfortable for White, but require entirely different responses. Unsurprisingly the 15th World Champion is up to the task. }
5... a6 6. Bd3
{ This move and the connected idea to play Ne4 is key to remember against 5... a6. }
6... Bg4 7. h3 Bh5 8. O-O Nc6 9. Ne4 Nxe4 10. Bxe4
{ White has accomplished something: He traded his badly placed Knight on c3 against the well placed Knight on f6. Why is c3 a bad square for the Knight ? Well, it is not so much that the Knight would be 'offside', but it blocks the c-pawn. This is important, as the c-pawn is a natural defender of the d4-pawn and also might be used more actively with pushing c2-c4. At the same time. An additional accomplishment is of course the strong Bishop on e4, looking at both sides of the board. }
10... e6 11. c3 Bg6
{ Black quite often emphasizes Queen side development in the Scandinavian, which makes castling long quite a frequent guest in this opening. Here it is very dubious though as White quickly launched the attack.   11...O-O-O  12.b4  This is both dangerous and simple to play - quite a terrible situation for Black. }
12. Bxc6+
{ A very interesting decision. White is giving up the Pair of Bishops because he is gaining lots of time to increase his initiative.  Something more standard like   12.Bxg6  hxg6  13.Re1  was also quite good for White, but less forceful. Note that Black has some King position issues here as well. Going long is questionable due to the hook on a6, while going short will also not be completely safe in view of a Knight possibly appearing on g5. }
12... Qxc6 13. Ne5 Qb6
{ This is more or less mandatory.  Instead   13...Qe4  14.Re1  Qf5  15.Qa4+  b5  16.Qb3  Bd6  17.a4  is excellent for White. }
14. c4
{ This is the most direct and aggressive move.  White had a good alternative in   14.a4  Black now should stop this pawn with  a5  Castling into it cannot be recommended.   14...O-O-O  15.b4  is awful for Black.  If Black plays something slow like   14...Bd6  the problem is  15.a5  Qa7  16.Qa4+  And Black is in bad shape again.  After 14.. ..a5 White may just play  15.Re1  correctly claiming that Black's position is not harmonious. It's tough to play c7-c5 and obtain counterplay. }
14... O-O-O
{ This is risky, but very principled. It immediately points at d4, the pawn weakness White just created. }
15. Be3
{ This is a critical position early in the game. Black now had the fundamental choice between allowing c4-c5 and stopping it. }
15... c5
{ Let's check alternatives.  First we need to get   15...Qxb2 ?  out of the way. This fails due to  16.Nxg6  hxg6  17.Rb1  Qxa2  18.Qf3  and Black is falling apart.  However a playable aternative was   15...Be7  16.c5  Qxb2  This is also quite risky, obviously, but things are not entirely clear and for sure not simple to play.  17.Nxg6  The tempting   17.c6  b6  18.a4  threatens to take on g6 and play Qd3, invading on a6. Black has only one defence.  Rd6 !  This surprisingly seems to hold.  19.Qf3  f6  20.Nxg6  hxg6  21.Rfc1  Rh4 !  is a possible line that is OK for Black.  17...fxg6   17...hxg6  18.Qf3  is worse as f7 is just hanging in addition to Rb1 being threatened.  18.Qg4  Qb5  19.Qxe6+  Qd7  20.Qb3  and White keeps the better chances, using the open b-file to attack. }
16. d5
{ Here Anand had a stronger move, one that he would have played for sure if he had more time to consider his options. It's a rapid game after all.   16.b4 !  The kind of move that makes you smile when you are allowed to play it. White gets an extremely strong attack now.  Qxb4  This is relatively best.  Other lines like   16...cxb4  17.c5  Qa5  18.Bf4  or   16...cxd4  17.c5  Qxb4  18.Bd2  Qb2  19.Rc1  crumble quickly.  17.Nxg6  hxg6  18.Rb1  Qxc4  19.Qf3  Qd5  20.Qxf7  Qd7  21.Qf4  and White is much better. }
16... Bd6
